    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi> | (<hi rend="print">Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi>)</placeName>
                    <date>December 21<hi rend="superscript">st</hi> 1881</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I must again have the pleasure of thanking you for another grand present of your magnificent work, “Das Gehörorgan der Wirbelthiere”.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> Notwithstanding the generous words written by you on the title-page, I cannot feel myself worthy of such a gift.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>With my sincere thanks &amp; much respect, I remain | My dear Sir | Yours faithfully &amp; obliged | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.1 (<hi rend="italic">Railway … S.E.R.</hi>)] <hi rend="italic">parentheses added</hi> </note>
            </div>
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Retzius sent the first volume of <hi rend="italic">Das Gehörorgan der Wirbelthiere</hi> (The acoustic organ of vertebrates; <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_9720.xml">Retzius 1881–4</ref>), which dealt with the acoustic organs of fishes and amphibians.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD’s copy of the first volume of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_9720.xml" resp="#automat" cert="low">Retzius 1881–4</ref> is in the Darwin Library–Down; the inscription reads ‘</note>  
        </div>
    
